TY  - JOUR
AU  - Dyck, A.
AU  - Pomorski, L.
T1  -  Investor Scale and Performance in Private Equity Investments *
PY  - 2016
Y1  - 2016/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfv030
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 20
IS  - 3
SP  - 1081
EP  - 1106
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - We document that defined benefit pension plans with significant holdings in private equity (PE) earn substantially greater returns than plans with small holdings, in both the 1990s and the 2000s. A one standard deviation increase in PE holdings is associated with 4% greater returns per year. Up to one-third of this outperformance comes from lower costs that we link to economizing on costly intermediation by avoiding fund-of-funds and investing directly. The bulk of the outperformance comes from superior gross returns only partially explained by access and experience. We conjecture that larger PE investors have superior due diligence and ability to bridge information asymmetries in PE.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfv030
ER  - 



